node.text:
A true weekend anthem. 💤 ⁣
⁣
Born July 31, 1897, Ignacio Fleta was one of the most important Spanish classical guitar builders of the 20th century. ⁣
⁣
This guitar in The Met collection, built by Fleta in 1953, is played here by Swedish musician Mattias Schulstad (@mattiasguitar).⁣
⁣
Did You Know: The term "Spanish guitar" has been used differently across time and cultures. Today it's often used interchangeably with the "classical guitar" and is certainly not limited to instruments made in Spain (though Ignacio Fleta was indeed from Spain).⁣
⁣
Learn more at the link in bio.⁣
⁣
🎶 "Come, Heavy Sleep (Molto Tranquillo)" from Nocturnal After John Dowland, op.70 by Benjamin Britten (1913–1976) ⁣
⁣🎸 Ignacio Fleta (Spanish, 1897–1977). Guitar, 1953. Spruce, rosewood. #MetMusic

⁣ ⁣⁣
⁣
"To Evan –⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
We emerge from isolation into a world both familiar⁣⁣⁣
And alien.⁣⁣⁣
We work tirelessly to keep the demons at bay,⁣⁣⁣
But still the damage is done.⁣⁣⁣
The smoke from the west reaches the east, and makes the south more violent ⁣⁣⁣
The north less predictable.⁣⁣⁣
One way out of this reality –⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Stay grounded⁣⁣⁣
Be attentive⁣⁣⁣
Connect⁣⁣⁣
And BREATHE"⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
—Matthew Evan Taylor (@matthewevantaylor⁣⁣⁣)⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
During a time plagued by isolation, how can musicians compose collaboratively when separated by vast distances? ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Tune in each month for #PostcardsToTheMet—a #MetLiveArts project from composer and solo saxophonist Matthew Evan Taylor's, in collaboration with Metropolis Ensemble and RAJAS. ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
This month's episode features musician Evan Runyon on double bass.⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Watch the full series on our IGTV channel for a glimpse into Taylor's creative process as he exchanges concepts with musicians across the globe for his piece "Life Returns," which will be presented at The Met in spring 2022.⁣⁣⁣⁣ Tap the link in bio for more.⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣

node.text:
📸 The New Woman of the 1920s was a powerful expression of modernity—a global phenomenon that embodied an ideal of female empowerment based on real women making revolutionary changes in life and art. ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Opening this Friday, July 2, "The New Woman Behind the Camera" explores the work of the diverse "new" women across the globe who embraced photography as a mode of professional and artistic expression from the 1920s through the 1950s, when women stood at the forefront of experimentation with the camera. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
Tap the link in bio to learn more—and tune in on July 8 (7 pm ET) for a virtual, curator-led tour through the exhibition. #NewWomanPhotographers ⁣@metphotographs
⁣
🎥 Video produced by The National Gallery of Art, Washington. @ngadc

⁣”To Rajna —⁣⁣
⁣
Unless we listen to our hearts,⁣⁣
Time will pass imperceptibly.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Once we listen to our hearts⁣⁣
We vocalize the future we wish to see.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The challenge—to make our marks within the time we have."⁣⁣
⁣⁣
In this month’s installment of #PostcardsToTheMet, hear the music of Rajna Swaminathan, acclaimed mrudangam musician.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
How can musicians compose collaboratively from across the globe? Tune in each month to this #MetLiveArts project from composer and solo saxophonist Matthew Evan Taylor, in collaboration with Metropolis Ensemble and RAJAS, for a glimpse into Taylor's creative process to exchange musical concepts globally for his piece "Life Returns," which will be presented at The Met in spring 2022.⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
Watch the full series on our IGTV channel, and tap the link in bio for more.⁣⁣

Hey #VirtualMuseumMile go-ers! Join us on a trip through the Temple of Dendur—a beloved gift from the Egyptian government to the U.S.

Built by Ceasar Augustus in 10 B.C., this monument is dedicated not only to the goddess Isis and other Egyptian deities, but also to several Indigenous Nubian gods and two local saints.

Keep an eye out for the Sphinx of Hatshepsut and other ancient Egyptian sculptures that surround the temple in Gallery 131.

node.title: Silent Gallery Tour—The Temple of Dendur

“My art is grounded in the belief of one universal energy which runs through everything—from insect to man, from man to specter, from specter to plant, from plant to galaxy." 

#AnaMendieta's interdisciplinary practice often blurred the boundaries between the manmade and the natural. Over her brief but prolific career, she created a rich body of work that fused her interests in Afro-Cuban religious traditions, feminist thought, and broader questions surrounding humanity's relationship to the land, often connecting her work with the surrounding ecology.

On #WorldEnviornmentDay, a look at Mendieta's life and work through this 1987 documentary, released two years after her death, provokes questions about our own relationships to our history, our surroundings, and our planet. #ArtforaHealthyPlanet 

📽️ Watch the hour-long film and explore more #FromTheVaults at the link in bio.

Photography meets DIY 📸

Hey @metteens! Today is #TeensTakeTheMet, so we've got a fun project to inspire you—create your own pinhole camera.

Before you begin, you'll need:

✔️ Cardboard Box with a Lid
✔️ Black Paint
✔️ Paint Brush
✔️ Aluminum Foil
✔️ Wax Paper
✔️ Black Electrical Tape
✔️ Pin or Toothpick
✔️ Scissors

Steps:
1️⃣ Paint your cardboard box black, inside and out. Pro tip: Give it a second coat of paint for extra coverage.

2️⃣ Using the outline of a cup, cut a circle into one side of the box. On the opposite side of the box, cut a 12 cm x 8 cm rectangle.

3️⃣ Cut a square of aluminum foil big enough to cover your circular hole, and tape it on the inside of the box. Using your pin (or toothpick), make a small hole in the center of the aluminum. This is your lens!

4️⃣ Cut a sheet of wax paper big enough to fit the rectangle hole and, tape it on the inside of the box. This will be the screen where you will see your image.

5️⃣ Tape the lid to the top of the box using your electrical tape.

6️⃣ Put a dark cloth over your head and point your camera towards a brightly lit area. You should be able to see an upside-down image in your box.

Bonus: Cut a small piece of cardboard to place over the lens. This will act as a lens cover!

Your pinhole camera is now ready for use! If you try this out, don't forget to share your creations with #TeensTakeTheMet. We can’t wait to see what you make!

P.S. Looking for more creative prompts? Head over to @metteens for more!

node.text:
Did You Know: The first recorded Olympic victor was Koroibos of Elis, who won the stadion (footrace) in 776 B.C. ⁣
⁣
By the sixth century B.C., Panhellenic games—from pan (all) and hellenikos (Greek)—were also held at Delphi, Nemea, and Isthmia and attracted athletes from all over the Greek world. Many local festivals, including the Panathenaia in Athens, were modeled on these four games.⁣
⁣
Each Panhellenic competition in ancient Greece—including the #OlympicGames, held every four years in honor of Zeus—was marked by a truce, or ekecheiria, which literally means “holding of hands." 🤝 ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The truce not only allowed athletes and fans to travel safely, but also provided a common basis for peace among the Greeks. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Pause that #Olympics2021 coverage and take a closer look at objects in The Met collection that tell stories about the ancient games.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Start reading at the link in bio.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
🎨 Attributed to the Euphiletos Painter. Terracotta Panathenaic prize amphora, ca. 530 B.C. Greece, Archaic period. @metgreekandroman

A year of self-isolation? Try a lifetime.⁣
⁣
Meet Shitao. After living as a monk for almost his entire life, in 1696 he decided to shed his Buddhist garb, abandon his nomadic lifestyle, and build roots in the commercial center of Yangzhou, where he supported himself through his painting. ⁣
⁣
These ink and color compositions come from an album he painted not long after his move—and are inspired by his lifetime of wandering.⁣
⁣
NOW ON VIEW: "Companions in Solitude: Reclusion and Communion in Chinese Art" explores the twin themes of solitude and togetherness in Chinese art over the span of more than 2,000 years—an apt subject of contemplation after the tumultuous year of 2020 that found many of us physically secluded but virtually together.⁣
⁣
Tap link in bio to learn more.⁣
⁣
🎨 Shitao (Zhu Ruoji), (Chinese, 1642–1707). Searching for Immortals (details), ca. 1690s. On view in Gallery 210. #MetChineseArt⁣

In honor of NYC #DisabilityPrideMonth, we're taking a (brief) look back at the history of accessible programming here at The Met.⁣
⁣
As early as 1908, the Museum began offering programs for Blind and Deaf visitors and providing wheelchairs on site. (This first photograph was taken in 1922.)⁣
⁣
In the 1970s The Met established its touch collection—a group of objects meant to aid Blind visitors in experiencing a work of art—as well as sign language tours and tours for groups of Disabled people.⁣
⁣
A decade later, The Met ​expanded programming for visitors with learning and developmental disabilities and those on the autism spectrum through the creation of the Discoveries program—which continues to this day!⁣
⁣
Today our #MetAccess program provides a range of activities, classes, and events ​both in-person and online that are tailored to meet the needs of visitors with disabilities. → Learn more at the link in bio.⁣
⁣
📸 The Metropolitan Museum of Art, Wing B, 1st Floor, Gallery 40: Cast Collection Galleries, November 23, 1922.⁣

node.text:
Mystery solved?! ⁣
⁣
We've long wondered about the identity of Elenka, painted by Alice Neel in 1936 and currently on view in "Alice Neel: People Come First."⁣
⁣
Thanks to Susan Felleman, professor of art history & film and media studies at the University of South Carolina, who visited the show recently, we now think we know. ⁣
⁣
Professor Felleman speculates that Elenka is actually the great experimental filmmaker Maya Deren. → Swipe to see her at age 19, before she changed her name. ⁣
⁣
Deren (born with the surname Derenkowska) was living in Greenwich Village and circulating in left-wing circles, as did Neel, in the mid 1930s. Her nickname as a child and well into her adulthood was Elinka (spelled with an “i”). A strong resemblance exists between the painting of Elenka and photographs of Deren from the period—do you agree?⁣
⁣
This exciting discovery caps off The Met's extraordinary run of the "Alice Neel: People Come First." Visit the exhibition for its final weekend before it closes August 1. 
⁣
🎨 Alice Neel (American, 1900–1984). Elenka, 1936. Gift of Richard Neel and Hartley S. Neel, 1987. © The Estate of Alice Neel⁣ @metmodern #MetAliceNeel
⁣
📸 Onondagan Yearbook, Syracuse University, Syracuse, New York, 1935, p. 70.⁣
